Fail tests > how to fail, and why it fails

1.	open()
	1.	Non-existent file name 
		Non-text files
	2.	Invalid mode.
		valid modes are - O_RDONLY, O_WRONLY OR O_RDWR
Answer - In all cases it returns a -1

2.	read()
	1.	Invalid files descriptor.          		--> return -1
	2.	file not open.						--> return -1
	2.	Invalid pointer to the buffer  		--> returns -1
		Not allocated valid memory             --> returns -1
	3.	buffer_size = 0 --> no error returned, returns 0
	4.	buffer_size < 0 					-->  returns -1

3.	malloc()
	You can't force malloc to fail.
	You can purposefully set pointer to NULL, right after malloc and see if the failure test condition take appropriate actions, like free() all previously malloced contiguous data.
